<section xml:id="critical-numbers-graphing-from-formulas-supplementary-exercises">
    <title>Supplement</title>
    <exercises>
        <exercisegroup>
            <introduction>
                <sidebyside>
                    <paragraphs valign="top">
                        <p>The sine and cosine function are called <term>circular trigonometric functions</term> because, for any given value of <m>t</m> the point <m>\point{\fe{\cos}{t}}{\fe{\sin}{t}}</m> lies on the circle with equation <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>. The area of the <q>pie slice</q> defined by the origin, <m>\point{1}{0}</m>, and the circular arc to <m>\point{\fe{\cos}{t}}{\fe{\sin}{t}}</m> is exactly <m>\frac{1}{2}t</m>.</p>
                    </paragraphs>
                    <figure valign="top">
                        <caption><m>\point{\fe{\cos}{t}}{\fe{\sin}{t}}</m> on the circle <m>x^2+y^2=1</m></caption>
                            <image>
                            <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xmin=-3,xmax=3,ymin=-3,ymax=3,xtick={9},ytick={9},unit vector ratio*=1 1 1, clip=false]
                                \addplot[pccplot,domain=0:360,-,variable=t]({cos(t)},{sin(t)});
                                \addplot[-] coordinates {(0.8,0.6) (0,0)};
                                \addplot[mark=*] coordinates {(0.8,0.6)} node[pin={$(\fe{\cos}{t},\fe{\sin}{t})$}]{} ;
                            \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                            </latex-image-code>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
                <sidebyside>
                    <paragraphs valign="top"> 
                        <p>There are analogous functions called <term>hyperbolic sine</term> and <term>hyperbolic cosine</term>.  As you might suspect, these functions generate points that lie on a hyperbola; specifically, for all values of <m>t</m>, the point <m>\point{\fe{\cosh}{t}}{\fe{\sinh}{t}}</m> lies on the hyperbola <m>x^2-y^2=1</m>. The area of the <q>shark fin</q> defined by the origin, <m>\point{1}{0}</m>, and the hyperbolic arc to <m>\point{\fe{\cosh}{t}}{\fe{\sinh}{t}}</m> is exactly <m>\frac{1}{2}t</m>.</p>
                    </paragraphs>
                    <figure valign="top">
                        <caption><m>\point{\fe{\cosh}{t}}{\fe{\sinh}{t}}</m> on the hyperbola <m>x^2-y^2=1</m></caption>
                            <image>
                            <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \begin{axis}[xmin=-3,xmax=3,ymin=-3,ymax=3,xtick={9},ytick={9},unit vector ratio*=1 1 1, clip=false]
                                \addplot[pccplot,domain=-1.76275:1.76275,variable=t]({(exp(t)+exp(-t))/2},{(exp(t)-exp(-t))/2});
                                \addplot[pccplot,domain=-1.76275:1.76275,variable=t]({-(exp(t)+exp(-t))/2},{-(exp(t)-exp(-t))/2});
                                \addplot[-] coordinates {(1.5,1.11803399) (0,0)};
                                \addplot[mark=*] coordinates {(1.5,1.11803399)} node[pin=170:{$(\fe{\cosh}{t},\fe{\sinh}{t})$}]{} ;
                            \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                            </latex-image-code>
                        </image>
                    </figure>
                </sidebyside>
                <p>It turns out that there are formulas for these hyperbolic trigonometric functions in terms of functions we already know.  Specifically:<md><mrow>\fe{\cosh}{t}&amp;=\frac{e^{t}+e^{-t}}{2}&amp;\fe{\sinh}{t}&amp;=\frac{e^{t}-e^{-t}}{2}</mrow></md></p> 
            </introduction>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Use the exponential formulas to verify the identity <m>\fe{\cosh^2}{t}-\fe{\sinh^2}{t}=1</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>\fe{\cosh^2}{t}-\fe{\sinh^2}{t}&amp;=\left(\frac{e^{t}+e^{-t}}{2}\right)^2-\left(\frac{e^{t}-e^{-t}}{2}\right)^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{e^{2t}+2+e^{-2t}}{4}-\frac{e^{2t}-2+e^{-2t}}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{4}{4}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=1</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p>See the solutions section.</p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Use the exponential formulas to determine the first derivatives (with respect to <m>t</m>) of <m>\fe{\cosh}{t}</m> and <m>\fe{\sinh}{t}</m>.  Determine, by inference, the second derivative formulas for each of these functions.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><md>
                    <mrow>\lzoo{t}{\fe{\cosh}{t}}&amp;=\lzoo{t}{\frac{e^{t}+e^{-t}}{2}}&amp;\lzoo{t}{\fe{\sinh}{t}}&amp;=\lzoo{t}{\frac{e^{t}-e^{-t}}{2}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\frac{e^{t}-e^{-t}}{2}&amp;&amp;=\frac{e^{t}+e^{-t}}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\fe{\sinh}{t}&amp;&amp;=\fe{\cosh}{t}</mrow>
                    </md>It follows that <m>\lzon{2}{t}{\fe{\cosh}{t}}=\fe{\cosh}{t}</m> and <m>\lzon{2}{t}{\fe{\sinh}{t}}=\fe{\sinh}{t}</m>.</p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>\lzoo{t}{\fe{\cosh}{t}}=\fe{\sinh}{t}</m>, <m>\lzoo{t}{\fe{\sinh}{t}}=\fe{\cosh}{t}</m>, <m>\lzon{2}{t}{\fe{\cosh}{t}}=\fe{\cosh}{t}</m> and <m>\lzon{2}{t}{\fe{\sinh}{t}}=\fe{\sinh}{t}</m></p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise xml:id="exercise-critical-hyperbolic">
                <statement>
                    <p>Determine the critical numbers of <m>\cosh</m> and <m>\sinh</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>The domains of both <m>\cosh</m> and <m>\sinh</m> are <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{\infty}</m>. Both functions' derivatives are always defined, so the only issue is when the derivatives equal <m>0</m>.<md>
                    <mrow>\lzoo{t}{\fe{\cosh}{t}}&amp;=0&amp;\lzoo{t}{\fe{\sinh}{t}}&amp;=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>\fe{\sinh}{t}&amp;=0&amp;\fe{\cosh}{t}&amp;=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{e^{t}-e^{-t}}{2}&amp;=0&amp;\frac{e^{t}+e^{-t}}{2}&amp;=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>e^{t}&amp;=e^{-t}&amp;&amp;</mrow>
                    <mrow>e^{2t}&amp;=1&amp;&amp;</mrow>
                    <mrow>t&amp;=0&amp;&amp;</mrow>
                    </md>The only critical number for <m>\cosh</m> is <m>0</m>. The function <m>\sinh</m> has no critical numbers, since <m>\frac{e^{t}+e^{-t}}{2}</m> is always positive.</p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p>The only critical number for <m>\cosh</m> is <m>0</m>. The function <m>\sinh</m> has no critical numbers.</p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise>
                <statement>
                    <p>Determine the intervals over which <m>\cosh</m> and <m>\sinh</m> are increasing/decreasing and over which they are concave up/concave down.</p> 
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p><m>\fe{\sinh}{t}</m> is positive on <m>\ointerval{0}{\infty}</m> and negative on <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{0}</m>. Since <m>\lzoo{t}{\fe{\cosh}{t}}=\fe{\sinh}{t}</m> and <m>\lzon{2}{t}{\fe{\sinh}{t}}=\fe{\sinh}{t}</m>, it follows that <m>\cosh</m> is increasing on <m>\ointerval{0}{\infty}</m> and decreasing on <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{0}</m>, while <m>\sinh</m> is concave up on <m>\ointerval{0}{\infty}</m> and concave down on <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{0}</m>.</p>
                    <p><m>\fe{\cosh}{t}</m> is positive on all of <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{\infty}</m>. Since <m>\lzoo{t}{\fe{\sinh}{t}}=\fe{\cosh}{t}</m> and <m>\lzon{2}{t}{\fe{\cosh}{t}}=\fe{\cosh}{t}</m>, it follows that <m>\sinh</m> is increasing on <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{\infty}</m> and <m>\cosh</m> is concave up on <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{\infty}</m>.</p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>\cosh</m> is increasing on <m>\ointerval{0}{\infty}</m>, decreasing on <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{0}</m>, and concave up on <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{\infty}</m>; <m>\sinh</m> is increasing on <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{\infty}</m>, concave up on <m>\ointerval{0}{\infty}</m>, and concave down on <m>\ointerval{-\infty}{0}</m></p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
            <exercise xml:id="exercise-hyperbolic-limits">
                <statement>
                    <p>Use the exponential formulas to determine each of the following limits: <m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}\fe{\cosh}{t}</m>, <m>\lim\limits_{t\to\infty}\fe{\cosh}{t}</m>, <m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}\fe{\sinh}{t}</m>, and <m>\lim\limits_{t\to\infty}\fe{\sinh}{t}</m>.</p>
                </statement>
                <solution>
                    <p>Each of the hyperbolic limits can be found quickly using these four basic limits: <m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}e^t=0</m>, <m>\lim\limits_{t\to\infty}e^t=\infty</m>, <m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}e^{-t}=\infty</m>, <m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}e^{-t}=0</m>.<md>
                    <mrow>\lim_{t\to-\infty}\fe{\cosh}{t}&amp;=\lim_{t\to-\infty}\frac{e^{t}+e^{-t}}{2}&amp;\lim_{t\to\infty}\fe{\cosh}{t}&amp;\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{e^{t}+e^{-t}}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=\infty&amp;&amp;=\infty</mrow>
                    <mrow>\lim_{t\to-\infty}\fe{\sinh}{t}&amp;=\lim_{t\to-\infty}\frac{e^{t}-e^{-t}}{2}&amp;\lim_{t\to\infty}\fe{\sinh}{t}&amp;\lim_{t\to\infty}\frac{e^{t}-e^{-t}}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>&amp;=-\infty&amp;&amp;=\infty</mrow>
                    </md></p>
                </solution>
                <answer>
                    <p><m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}\fe{\cosh}{t}=\lim\limits_{t\to\infty}\fe{\cosh}{t}=\lim\limits_{t\to\infty}\fe{\sinh}{t}=\infty</m>; <m>\lim\limits_{t\to-\infty}\fe{\sinh}{t}=-\infty</m></p>
                </answer>
            </exercise>
